Project 1 - Understanding Happiness Levels in The Americas¶

Introduction¶

It is important for the leaders of the world to understand the happiness levels of the people they represent. Thus, I consider that analyzing the factors that are involved to people's happiness is an interesting subject. Also, it is interesting to learn what countries are considered the happiest and what other factors they have that can add to those happiness levels. Thus, compared to other countries with lower happiness ranking.

The main goal of this project is to understand the happiness levels in North, Central, and South America over the years (2016, 2017, 2018, 2019). This is with the intention of understanding the importance that each category imply to the happiness of each country. They are a couple of fields that are taken into consideration when it comes to determining the happiness levels of a country such as Economy, Family, Health, Freedom, Trust Government Corruption, Generosity, and Dystopia (which will not be taken into consideration). Those fields contribute to the final rank of happiness in these datasets.

What this project will try to solve is how happiness in countries can vary, what are the main attributes that contribute to these changes, check if there are countries that have changed their rank and what was the main factor, and compare the conditions of different countries to understand if there is a same factor.

It is important to highlight that the data is limited.

This Dataset is found on this following link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/unsdsn/world-happiness/data

Pre-processing Data¶

I would consider these datasets to be clean datasets. However, the datasets are world-wide. Thus, I will be only modifying the set to make sure I only get values in the Americas, and I will go from there to check that all the other cleaning steps are done.

I first start with importing the libraries we will be using for this project and loading everything.

Fixing Datasets¶

I noticed that the column names were long for me to be able to work with them easily. Thus, I decided to trim the name of the columns and adapt the naming to the dataset from 2016. Here is relevant information that was cut off the naming of the fields:

  • Economy - GDP per Capita
  • Health - Life Expectancy
  • Trust - Government Corruptions

Also, although the Low Confidence and High Confidence intervals are good to have, they are not relevant to the type of solution this project is aiming for so I will be dropping them. I also dropped the Dystopia field because the dataset says it is supposed to be an imaginary country with the least economy, health, trust, etc. However, they added this imaginary value to the score of each country as a type to showcase that each country has some magic field for happiness (unexplained happiness). For the purpose of this project, I will be not considering that imaginary value.

Data Visualizations¶

After making sure that the data was proper for the different visuals, here are some visuals I decided to use to analyze the data and understand different aspects of it. Now, it is time to use some visualizations to answer the questions described in the introduction:

  • How happiness in countries can vary?
  • What are the main 3 attributes that contribute to happiness scores?
  • Are there countries that have changed their rank and what was the main factor?

Happiness Score Changes Throughout the Years¶

This is an individual overview of each country. I wanted to see if there were any countries that have had a drastic change in happiness scores in the years of 2016-2019. After the visualization, the countries that have a noticable change in their score are the following:

  • Venezuela
  • jamaica
  • Honduras
  • Haiti

I believe that the other countries, althought it is not precisely a straight horizontal line, have somewhat enough balance when it comes to their scores in the different years

Finding Factors for Countries Without Stable Happiness Scores¶

After fiding what countries were the most ustable happiness scores, I wanted to see what the factors were for that change and if there was a common denominator of the change as well. Thus, we can see that:

  • Haiti: has the most change in health and social support
  • Honduras: has the most change in social support, health, and freedom
  • Jamaica: has the most change in social support and generosity
  • Venezuela: has the most change in economy, health, and social support

Happiness Score Aspects in Different Years¶

I was curious to see if there was a remarkable difference from country to country troughout the years. It seems like the countries keep the same factors that can contribute to the final happiness score. However, something that I found interesting is that for some countries, the trust in their government (agaisnt corruption) used to the be way higher in 2016 compared to the other year.

In [32]:
def plot_stacked_bar(df):
    width = 0.5
    bottom = np.zeros(len(df))
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,6))

    for key, value in df.items():
        if (key!='Country')&(key!='Year')&(key!='Happiness Score'):
            p = ax.bar(df['Country'], value, width, label=key, bottom=bottom)
            bottom += value

    ax.set_title('Factors contributing to Each Score in ' + df['Year'].iloc[0])
    ax.legend()
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
    
plot_stacked_bar(df_2016)
plot_stacked_bar(df_2017)
plot_stacked_bar(df_2018)
plot_stacked_bar(df_2019)

plt.show()

Conclusion¶

I would like to, once again, repeat that this dataset was a pretty small one. Another thing that I would like to point out is that the description for these datasets was somewhat broad. Thus, I decided to still showcase my work keeping in mind that there are some assumptions that can be made.

One of the assumptions was the Dystopia score, which was an imaginary country and its happiness level. This score was added to the final happiness score of each country plus the leftover of score that could not be justified in any of the categories below, thus, a imaginary number. Therefore, I decided to only use these categories:

  • Economy
  • Health
  • Trust
  • Generosity
  • Social Support
  • Freedom

Which means that, for the purpose of this project, I am assuming that the scores/percentages score of each category will add up to what the happiness score is. The resource for the numbers was not found so I cannot corroborate that the assumption is right.

After that being said, I believe that there is a relationship between the happiness score and the categories represented. It seems like one of the most important categories for happiness is a country is the Social Suport of each country (can be from family, friends, known people, etc). However, Economy (GDP Per Capita) and Health are pretty close, making Economy, Health, and Social Support the top 3 factors related to happiness in a country.

The countries with a more drastic change throughout the years 2016-2019 are (either up and down):

  • Venezuela
  • jamaica
  • Honduras
  • Haiti

One common denominator that I found for those 4 countries is that they have a bigger change in social support and social support is their strogest factor.

To conclude, most countries have steady happiness scores from 2016-2019 and, generally, the top three factors that can highlight the happiness of a country are: social support, economy, and health.
